{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-26",
    "title": "Academic Distancing: The Impersonal Passive",
    "description": "Learning how to talk about beliefs or general facts objectively (It is thought that...).",
    "display_order": 26,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-25"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# Academic Distancing: Impersonal Passive\n\nIn science and academic writing, you must sound objective. Instead of saying \"I think that...\" or \"Many people believe that...\", we use the **Impersonal Passive** to distance ourselves from the opinion.\n\n### 1. Form A: \"It is + V3 + that\"\nUse this to report a general belief or claim.\n- **Formula**: It + is + V3 + that + (the fact)\n- **Example**: **It is said that** the university was founded in 1950.\n- **Example**: **It is believed that** climate change is a serious threat.\n\n### 2. Form B: \"The subject + is + V3 + to be\"\nThis is a more direct way to focus on the object.\n- **Formula**: Subject + is + V3 + to + V1\n- **Example**: The library **is thought to be** the largest in the country.\n- **Example**: The species **is believed to exist** only on this island.\n\n### 3. Common Verbs\n- say \u2192 **said**\n- believe \u2192 **believed**\n- think \u2192 **thought**\n- know \u2192 **known**\n- consider \u2192 **considered**\n\n---",
